‘'Reductto od impossibile. This phrase, though sanctioned by respectable authorities, is incorrect3 as may be shewn by substituting the definition. What is the meaning of “the change of an imperfectio a perfect mood to the impossible 22¹¹ The error has been caused by the Aristotelian expression, ἀπαγωγὴ εἰς πὸ dodum in which, however, ἀπαγωγὴ does not mean reduction. The deductio od impossibile, as it is usually rendered, (obductio would perhaps be betten) is one species of the συλλογισμὸς ἐξ ὑποθέσεως, (see Appendix, note G‚) the object of which is, to prove the truth of a given problem, by inferring a falsehood from the assumption of its contradictory. This may beemployed in the reduction of syllogisms but it is also used for other purposes, as by Geometers. (Euchd. i. 7.) The correct expression is therefore Reductio per deductionem od impossibile, or elliptioally, Reductio per impossibile. The ἀπαγωγὴ of An. Pr. ii. 25. will be explained hereafter.

Any mood may be reduced by the deductio od impossibile, though in practice it is usually confined to Baroko and Bokardo.
